R E H A B

This ain't Amy Winehouse stuff. I'm REPOSTING ( previously on my Facebook ) four graphics from a series called rehab which is a fruit of what I learnt in the rehab phase of my life. I'm doing this because I really feel a lot of us need this out there. 
Guess what? Everyone needs rehabilitation in life. These may for be addictions or behavioural strongholds or whatever. There is nothing shameful with wanting to sort your life out and it is important that we identify the major issues in our lives and deal with them before they start breaking us. You need REHAB TIME! Not inside a real rehabilitation but in your personal life. And God, the greatest counselor ever, guides us through, smoothly, and surely. 
Here are some lessons I've learnt In the next Four posts.

A blue-winged demoiselle on a wood spurge, and how to fake death to avoid being harassed by males
This pic, taken two weeks ago next to a small creek in Périgord, shows a female blue-winged demoiselle (Calopteryx virgo) sitting on a wood spurge (Euphorbia amygdaloides). In this European damselfly, the male has metallic blue body, whereas the female (shown here) has dark brown iridescent wings, a white patch near the tip of the wings and a metallic green body with a bronze tip of the abdomen. The following story (communicated by my brother in law) was published this year in the series called “The Scientific Naturalist” of the journal “Ecology”. In this new series, scientists describe for a wide audience something important for ecological science that represent a scientific “aha” or “wow” moment in their research. Rassim Khelifa, from the University of Zurich, explains that on 5 July 2015 in the Swiss Alps, while he was waiting at a pond, at about 2000 m elevation, for his work on the effect of climate change in odonates, he witnessed a dragonfly dive to the ground while being pursued by another dragonfly. The individual that crashed was a female and was lying motionless and upside down on the ground. The other insect, a male, hovered above the female for a couple seconds and then left. The female was not unconscious after her crash landing as it flew away quickly as Rassim approached her. So he wondered if the female was faking death to avoid male harassment. Sexual death feigning is one of the rarest behaviors in nature, reported only in a handful of arthropods. His further observations and experiments confirmed this hypothesis. He observed tens of cases of females performing death feigning and showed that as a consequence of this behavior they undergo less coercion by males. This is important because the females are particularly vulnerable during oviposition, male harassment is costly for them and the sex ratio in these sites is biased towards males, thereby putting the females under extreme reproductive conditions: this rare behavior thus makes sense from an evolutionary perspective.

No matter how hard a teacher tries, there will always be those kids who act out in class. You know the ones—they miss questions from daydreaming, randomly shout disruptive things, and take part in other miscellaneous clowning and buffoonery. So, what do you do? According to a 2016 study, psychological control is not the answer. The study states, "These distinct mechanisms may have implications for educators." Instead of meeting disruption with stern hostility, it's best to really understand what's going on with your student. They'll likely daydream less, retain more, and cut back on their clownery.
